never-before-seen ways. The new ecology emphasizes the importance of conserving species diversity, because it can offer a portfolio of options to keep our ecosystems resilient in the face of environmental change. It envisions humans taking on new roles as thoughtful stewards of the environment to ensure that ecosystems have the enduring capacity to supply the environmental services on which our economic well-being-and our very existence-depend. It offers the ecological know-how to maintain and enhance our planet's environmental performance and ecosystem production for the benefit of current and future generations.Informative and engaging, The New Ecology shows how today's ecology can provide the insights we need to appreciate the crucial role we play in this era of unprecedented global environmental transition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEcology. 0aHuman ecology. 0aNaturexEffect of human beings on. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aNew Ecology.  aadaptive capacity.  aanimal rights.  aanimal welfare.  aanthropocentrism.  abiodiversity.  acod fishery.  aconservation.  adomesticating nature.  aecocentrism.  aecological functions.  aecologists.  aecology.  aecosystem functions.  aecosystem services.  aecosystems.  aenvironmental change.  aenvironmental policy.  aenvironmental stewardship.  aethics.  ahuman/nature divide.  ahumanity.  ahumans.  ahumanЮature divide.  aindustrial ecology.  anatural world.  anature.  anonanthropocentric ethics.  aplasticity.  aresilience.  asociety.  asocio-ecological systems.  aspecies diversity.  aspecies.  asustainability.  atechnology.  aurban ecology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054332240uh